{60285=AMES, Iowa (Ticker) -- Missouri defensive back A.J. Kincade 
gave Colorado an early Christmas present.

Kincade's interception in the end zone sealed Missouri's 17-14
overtime victory over Iowa State and sent Colorado to next
week's Big 12 championship game against Oklahoma.

Iowa State (6-5, 4-4 Big 12 North) could have clinched the
division with a victory.  Instead, Colorado won a tiebreaker
over the Cylones and will represent the division in the Big 12
title game despite a .500 record in the conference.

After Adam Crossett's 25-yard field goal gave Missouri (5-6, 3-5
North) the lead on the first possession of overtime, Iowa State
was in position for the winning score, reaching a 1st-and-goal
at the 3.

But two running plays by Stevie Hicks resulted in a loss of
three yards.  On third down, Kincade stepped in front of Bret
Meyer's pass intended for Jon Davis, snapping Missouri's
four-game losing streak.

On the first play of Iowa's overtime possession, a wide-open Ben
Barkema dropped a sure touchdown pass.

The Cyclones could have taken the lead late in the fourth
quarter, but Bret Culbertson badly missed a 24-yard field goal
to the right with 1:02 left.

Meyer completed 16-of-28 passes for 206 yards and rushed for 61
yards and a TD on 20 carries for the Cyclones, who erased
deficits of 7-0 and 14-7.  Iowa tied the contest, 14-14, on
Hicks' two-yard TD with 8:58 left in the fourth quarter.

Brad Smith completed 13-of-24 passes for 150 yards for Missouri.
He also ran for 101 yards on 21 carries, including a 36-yard
scamper that gave the Tigers a 14-7 lead with 5:48 left in the
third.}
